fields.special_kana_explanation: <SpecialKanaExplanation> <explanation> When you have a small つ, the next sound that comes after it is emphasized which means that the next letter that comes after it is written twice in romaji and is pronounced more strongly. </explanation>  <Examples> <SpecialKanaExplanationExample><AudioUrl>http://d1ymdibvv3e2ww.cloudfront.net/audio/kana/せっち.mp3</AudioUrl><KanaExample>せっち</KanaExample><RomajiExample>setchi</RomajiExample></SpecialKanaExplanationExample>,<SpecialKanaExplanationExample><AudioUrl>http://d1ymdibvv3e2ww.cloudfront.net/audio/kana/らっつ.mp3</AudioUrl><KanaExample>らっつ</KanaExample><RomajiExample>rattsu</RomajiExample></SpecialKanaExplanationExample>,<SpecialKanaExplanationExample><AudioUrl>http://d1ymdibvv3e2ww.cloudfront.net/audio/kana/まっぱ.mp3</AudioUrl><KanaExample>まっぱ</KanaExample><RomajiExample>mappa</RomajiExample></SpecialKanaExplanationExample> </Examples> </SpecialKanaExplanation>

<SpecialKanaExplanation> <explanation> When you have a small や, ゆ, or よ after a かな that ends in い, that い sound is replaced with the や, ゆ, or よ sound. This only applies to かな that end in い e.g き, し, ち ... or it's katakana equivalents. Also be sure to notice that for ち and し, you don't add a y in the romaji. For example, spelling しょ as shyo doesn't work, you just write sho. Same with if it was the other small ゆ, or よ. Shu, sho etc... same with ち. </explanation>  <Examples> <SpecialKanaExplanationExample><AudioUrl>http://d1ymdibvv3e2ww.cloudfront.net/audio/kana/みゃ.mp3</AudioUrl><KanaExample>みゃ</KanaExample><RomajiExample>mya</RomajiExample></SpecialKanaExplanationExample>,<SpecialKanaExplanationExample><AudioUrl>http://d1ymdibvv3e2ww.cloudfront.net/audio/kana/にゅ.mp3</AudioUrl><KanaExample>にゅ</KanaExample><RomajiExample>nyu</RomajiExample></SpecialKanaExplanationExample>,<SpecialKanaExplanationExample><AudioUrl>http://d1ymdibvv3e2ww.cloudfront.net/audio/kana/きょ.mp3</AudioUrl><KanaExample>きょ</KanaExample><RomajiExample>kyo</RomajiExample></SpecialKanaExplanationExample> </Examples> </SpecialKanaExplanation>

fields.mnemonic_explanation: Oh look, You can see a capital <bold>A</bold> in here!
You can notice a lowercase <bold>i</bold> except the dot on top is now a slash
Looks just like the hiragana う
Oh wow, look at all his <bold>e</bold>xtra bones
What an amazing <bold>o</bold>pera singer with his nice, flowing cape
This is the same shape as the hiragana version, か, but just without the slash on the top-right.
This is the same as the hiragana version き, except without the curve on the bottom

If you rotate this a bit you can see a k!
See the two <bold>co</bold>rners
Look at these two <bold>sa</bold>lmon hanging on the skewers!
Look at how happy <bold>she</bold> is with her two sideways eyes. And also quite a cool smiley face!
Here is <bold>su</bold>perman’s <bold>su</bold>it!
Remember how the せ katakana is made up of a bunch of 7’s? Now take one of them out and you get the katakana version!

Here is a needle and a long string for <bold>se</bold>wing. Remember that when you are sewing you need to put insert the needle almost vertically. This is important because this katakana is very similar to the katakana for ん so remembering this will help you differentiate them!
Look, it’s the <bold>To</bold>wer of Pisa!
A <bold>che</bold>ap antenna

ソ has one needle but this katakana has <bold>two</bold> needles! It is still important to remember that these are vertical needles as this differentiates this katakana from the シ katakana we learned earlier!
Look at these curvy <bold>te</bold>lephone poles!
Tick <bold>To</bold>ck, goes the clock
Look at this beautiful <bold>na</bold>rwhal
There are two <bold>nee</bold>dles here laying on their side
Grab the delicious <bold>no</bold>odles from the bowl with the chopsticks
What a cute horse that is <bold>ne</bold>ighing
This looks just like the slash in the middle of the の hiragana!
This looks like a big nose! Fun fact, nose in Japanese is <bold>ha</bold>na
Look at this man with his smile. <bold>He</bold> is so happy
This katakana looks just like a cliff. It must be really <bold>fu</bold>n to jump off this!
Hmmm, it’s almost as if it’s the same as the hiragana へ. Oh wait, they are!
A flying, <bold>ho</bold>ly cross
So many different angles and measurements in this katakana. This is too much <bold>ma</bold>th for me!
Oh no! So many <bold>mi</bold>ssiles coming at you
This looks just like a cow and it goes <bold>moo</bold>
This looks just like the inside X cross inside its hiragana counterpart め
This looks just like it’s hiragana version, も, except without the tip on top and more rigid
This looks just like it’s hiragana version, ヤ, except without the mark on the right and more rigid
This katakana is telling you that <bold>you</bold> are number one!
This person is doing an interesting <bold>yo</bold>ga stretch
There is a <bold>ra</bold>t enjoying the light on his cage
This looks just like it’s hiragana version, り, except more rigid
There are two <bold>ro</bold>utes for you to take.
She has beautiful, <bold>re</bold>d hair
Look at this square <bold>ro</bold>ad
This look strangely like a question mark, I wonder <bold>wha</bold>t it is?
Remember the happy lady with the two sideways eyes when we learned シ, now we have a happy ma<bold>n</bold> with one sideways eye
